      <h2>Who Pays for Title Insurance?</h2>

      <p>In Utah, it's customary (but negotiable) for the <strong>seller to pay for the owner's title insurance policy</strong> and the <strong>buyer to pay for the lender's policy</strong>. However, this is always part of the purchase negotiation. Your real estate agent can help negotiate these costs.</p>

      <h2>Common Title Issues We Find</h2>

      <p>You might think title problems are rare, but our team at OnRecord Title regularly discovers issues during the title search process. Some of the most common include:</p>

      <ul>
        <li><strong>Outstanding mortgages</strong> that weren't properly released after payoff</li>
        <li><strong>HOA liens</strong> for unpaid assessments</li>
        <li><strong>Property tax liens</strong> from previous owners</li>
        <li><strong>Judgment liens</strong> from lawsuits against previous owners</li>
        <li><strong>Errors in legal descriptions</strong> that need correction</li>
        <li><strong>Missing signatures</strong> on previous deeds or releases</li>
        <li><strong>Easements</strong> that restrict property use</li>
      </ul>

      <p>The good news? When we find these issues during the title search, we work to resolve them <em>before</em> closing so they don't become your problem. That's part of the value of working with an experienced title company.</p>

      <h2>What Title Insurance Doesn't Cover</h2>

      <p>Title insurance has some standard exceptions and exclusions:</p>

      <ul>
        <li>Defects or liens you created or agreed to</li>
        <li>Issues that would be revealed by a current survey (unless you get survey coverage)</li>
        <li>Government regulations (zoning, building codes) in standard policies</li>
        <li>Environmental contamination</li>
        <li>Native American claims on very old properties</li>
      </ul>

      <p>Many of these exceptions can be eliminated with <strong>enhanced coverage policies</strong> or specific endorsements. Talk to your title officer about what additional protections make sense for your situation.</p>

      <h2>Is Title Insurance Worth It?</h2>

      <p>Absolutely. Consider the math:</p>

      <ul>
        <li>A title insurance policy costs roughly <strong>0.5% of the purchase price</strong> — one time</li>
        <li>It protects an asset worth <strong>hundreds of thousands of dollars</strong></li>
        <li>Coverage lasts <strong>for as long as you own the property</strong></li>
        <li>The alternative is being personally liable for <strong>any title defects</strong></li>
      </ul>

      <p>No other form of insurance offers this kind of value — lifetime protection for a single premium.</p>

      <h2>How to Choose a Title Company</h2>

      <p>In Utah, you have the right to choose your title company. Here's what to look for:</p>

      <ul>
        <li><strong>Licensed and insured</strong> — Verify they're licensed with the Utah Insurance Department</li>
        <li><strong>Experienced staff</strong> — Look for dedicated title examiners and escrow officers</li>
        <li><strong>Communication</strong> — They should keep you informed throughout the process</li>
        <li><strong>Technology</strong> — Modern title companies offer online tracking and digital options</li>
        <li><strong>Flexibility</strong> — Mobile closings, online closings, and convenient scheduling</li>
        <li><strong>Transparent pricing</strong> — No hidden fees or surprises at closing</li>
      </ul>

